class Plots:
    def transaction_histogram(self, transaction_data):
        ## Histogram
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
        sns.histplot(
            transaction_data["transactionAmount"], bins=50, kde=True, color="blue"
        )
        ## Labels
        plt.title("Histogram of Transaction Amounts")
        plt.xlabel("Transaction Amount ($)")
        plt.ylabel("Frequency")
        plt.show()
    def transaction_boxplot(self, transaction_data):
        ## Box Plot
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 2))
        sns.boxplot(
            x=transaction_data["transactionAmount"],
            color="green"
        )
        ## Labels
        plt.title("Box Plot of Transaction Amounts")
        plt.xlabel("Transaction Amount ($)")
        plt.show()

3. Data Wrangling¶

3.1 Reverse Transaction and Multi-Swipe Transactions¶
In [14]:
class DuplicateTransaction:
    def reverse_transactions(self, transaction_data, tz):
        purchase_transaction = transaction_data[
            transaction_data["transactionType"] == "PURCHASE"
        ]
        reversal_transaction = transaction_data[
            transaction_data["transactionType"] == "REVERSAL"
        ]
        reverse_df = reversal_transaction.merge(
            purchase_transaction,
            on=["accountNumber", "customerId", "transactionAmount", "merchantName"],
            suffixes=("_reversal", "_purchase"),
        )
        ## Assumtion that reversal will be considered (5 minutes)
        reverse_df = reverse_df[
            abs(
                reverse_df["transactionDateTime_reversal"]
                - reverse_df["transactionDateTime_purchase"]
            )
            < pd.Timedelta(minutes=tz)
        ]
        return reverse_df

    def multiswipe_transactions(self, transaction_data, tz):
        purchase_transaction = transaction_data[
            transaction_data["transactionType"] == "PURCHASE"
        ]
        purchase_transaction = purchase_transaction.sort_values(
            by=[
                "accountNumber",
                "merchantName",
                "transactionAmount",
                "transactionDateTime",
            ]
        )
        purchase_transaction["prev_time"] = purchase_transaction.groupby(
            ["accountNumber", "merchantName", "transactionAmount"]
        )["transactionDateTime"].shift(1)
        purchase_transaction["time_diff"] = (
            purchase_transaction["transactionDateTime"]
            - purchase_transaction["prev_time"]
        ).dt.total_seconds()

        ## Short-time spam assumed to be less than equal to 1 minutes (60 seconds)
        multi_swipe_df = purchase_transaction[
            purchase_transaction["time_diff"] <= tz * 60
        ]
        return multi_swipe_df


duplicate = DuplicateTransaction()
reverse_df = duplicate.reverse_transactions(transaction_data, 5)
num_reverse = len(reverse_df)
sum_reverse_transaction = reverse_df["transactionAmount"].sum()

multi_swipe_df = duplicate.multiswipe_transactions(transaction_data, 1)
num_multiswipe = len(multi_swipe_df)
sum_multiswipe_transaction = multi_swipe_df["transactionAmount"].sum()

Insights from Multiswipe & Reverse Transactions¶

Reversed and multi-swipe transactions are frequent but typically non-fraudulent. However:

  • Certain merchants and customers are outliers in frequency and requires monitoring
  • Fraud rates, though low, are not negligible among multi-swipes, making them a good candidate for rule-based flagging in real-time systems.
  • The overall $1.2M+ total dollar amount involved in such duplicates highlights the importance of proactive mitigation.

Removing redundant transaction data (Multi swipe and reverse)¶
  • Multi-swipe transactions include repeated transactions (beyond the first within a short time window)- Including these in the dataset may introduce noise or bias the model. Therefore, are excluded from modeling
  • Given the severe class imbalance (many more non-fraudulent transactions), we apply random undersampling on the isFraud = False class. To further reduce redundancy and improve signal clarity, we also remove reversal transactions where isFraud == False, as they are not informative for fraud detection.

Transformation to be performed

  • Null values to be replaced by most frequent
  • Numerical columns to be scaled using Standard Scaler
  • High cardinality columns to be encoded using Target Encoding
  • Categorical columns to be encoded using One Hot Encoding
  • Downsampling for handling Data Inbalance
In [28]:
# Split features and target
y = df_data["isFraud"]
X = df_data.drop(columns=["isFraud"])

numerical_columns = [col for col in numerical_columns if col in X.columns]
high_cardinality_columns = [col for col in high_cardinality_columns if col in X.columns]
low_cardinality_columns = [col for col in low_cardinality_columns if col in X.columns]
## preprocessing pipelines
numerical_pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps=[
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
        ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
    ]
)

high_card_pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps=[
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
        ("target_encoder", TargetEncoder()),
    ]
)

low_card_pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps=[
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
        ("onehot", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore", sparse_output=False)),
    ]
)

## ColumnTransformer
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ("num", numerical_pipeline, numerical_columns),
        ("high_card_cat", high_card_pipeline, high_cardinality_columns),
        ("low_card_cat", low_card_pipeline, low_cardinality_columns),
    ]
)

X_preprocessed = preprocessor.fit_transform(X, y)

with open("pickle_files/preprocessing_pipeline.pkl", "wb") as f:
    pickle.dump(preprocessor, f)

print("Before undersampling:")
print("X shape:", X_preprocessed.shape)
print("y distribution:", y.value_counts())

## Undersample - handling Imbalance
undersample = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy="auto", random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = undersample.fit_resample(X_preprocessed, y)

print("\nAfter undersampling:")
print("X shape:", X_resampled.shape)
print("y distribution:", pd.Series(y_resampled).value_counts())

def evaluate_model(model, X_test, y_test, plot, model_name, threshold):
    if model_name == "ANN":
        y_prob = model.predict(X_test).flatten()  
    else:
        y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

    y_pred = (y_prob >= threshold).astype(int)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

    res = {
        "F1 Score": round(f1, 2),
        "Precision": round(precision, 2),
        "Recall": round(recall, 2),
        "Accuracy": round(accuracy, 2),
        "AUC-ROC": round(auc, 2),
    }
    res_df = pd.DataFrame([res])

    ## Confusion - Matrix
    if plot:
        print(f"Confusion Matrix with {threshold}")
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues")
        plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix - {model_name}")
        plt.show()

        ## AUC-ROC
        print("\nAUC-ROC Curve")
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"AUC {model_name} = {auc:.2f}")
        plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], "k--")
        plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
        plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
        plt.title(f"ROC Curve - {model_name}")
        plt.legend()
        plt.grid(True)
        plt.show()

    print(res_df)
    return res_df, res, fpr, tpr, auc, threshold

Modeling Approach (Model Traing , Evaluation and Comparison)¶

  • The analysis will be performed on 4 ML models - Logistic Rgression, Random Forest, XGBoost, ANN
  • For each of the model the best paramaters will be obtained using grid search CV
  • Metric - F1 Score, Precision, Recall and AUC-ROC will be compared for deciding on the best model
  • Additionally, Since the data was imbannce and handled using downsampling- it will be intersting to observe the behavior on varing the threshold (0.5, 0.4 and 0.6 resp.)
  • Finally, based on the metric for each case the final model for a specific threshold will be chose and feature importance will be evaluated to decide on most import feature

Logistic Regression - Baseline¶
In [32]:
def train_logistic_regression(X_train, y_train):
    param_grid = {"C": [0.01, 0.1, 1, 10], "penalty": ["l2"], "solver": ["lbfgs"]}
    grid = GridSearchCV(
        LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000), param_grid, scoring="f1", cv=3
    )
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print("Best Params for Logistic Regression:", grid.best_params_)
    return grid.best_estimator_
In [33]:
def run_logi(threshold):
    logistic_model = train_logistic_regression(X_train, y_train)
    lg_df, lg_res, lg_fpr, lg_tpr, lg_auc, threshold = evaluate_model(
        logistic_model, X_test, y_test, plot=True, model_name="Logistic Regression", threshold = threshold
    )
    all_metrics.append(lg_res)
    auc_data.append((lg_fpr, lg_tpr, lg_auc))
    lg_df
    ## Save the model
    with open(f"pickle_files/{threshold}_logistic_model.pkl", "wb") as f:
        pickle.dump(logistic_model, f)

def train_random_forest(X_train, y_train):
    param_grid = {
        "n_estimators": [100, 200],
        "max_depth": [5, 10, None],
        "min_samples_split": [2, 5],
    }
    grid = GridSearchCV(RandomForestClassifier(), param_grid, scoring="f1", cv=3)
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print("Best Params for Random Forest", grid.best_params_)
    return grid.best_estimator_

def train_xgboost(X_train, y_train):
    param_grid = {
        "n_estimators": [100, 200],
        "max_depth": [3, 6],
        "learning_rate": [0.01, 0.1],
        "subsample": [0.8, 1],
    }
    grid = GridSearchCV(
        XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric="logloss"),
        param_grid,
        scoring="f1",
        cv=3,
    )
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print("Best Params for XG-Boost", grid.best_params_)
    return grid.best_estimator_

In [41]:
def create_ann(hidden_layer_sizes=(64,), alpha=0.0001, learning_rate_init=0.001):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(
        Dense(
            hidden_layer_sizes[0],
            input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],),
            activation="relu",
            kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(alpha),
        )
    )

    for units in hidden_layer_sizes[1:]:
        model.add(
            Dense(units, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(alpha))
        )

    model.add(Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))

    optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate_init)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss="binary_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model


def train_ann(X_train, y_train):
    model = KerasClassifier(model=create_ann, verbose=0)

    param_grid = {
        "model__hidden_layer_sizes": [(64,), (128,), (64, 32), (16, 32, 32)],
        "model__alpha": [0.0001, 0.001],
        "model__learning_rate_init": [0.001, 0.01],
        "batch_size": [32],
        "epochs": [100],
    }

    grid = GridSearchCV(
        estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, scoring="f1", cv=3, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2
    )
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

    print("Best Params ANN:", grid.best_params_)
    return grid.best_estimator_.model_

def run_ann(threshold):
    ann_model = train_ann(X_train, y_train)
    ann_df, ann_res, ann_fpr, ann_tpr, ann_auc, threshold = evaluate_model(
        ann_model, X_test, y_test, plot=True, model_name="ANN", threshold = threshold
    )
    all_metrics.append(ann_res)
    auc_data.append((ann_fpr, ann_tpr, ann_auc))
    ann_df
    ## Save the model
    with open(f"pickle_files/{threshold}_ann_model.pkl", "wb") as f:
        pickle.dump(ann_model, f)

In [45]:
def model_analysis(threshold):
    models = ["Logistic Regression", "Random Forest", "XG Boost", "ANN"]
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(all_metrics, index=models)

    # Plot AUC-ROC for all models
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    for i, (fpr, tpr, auc) in enumerate(auc_data):
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"{models[i]}  = {auc:.2f}")
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], "k--", label="Random Classifier")
    plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    plt.title(f"AUC-ROC Curve for All Models - threshold={threshold}")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

    # Display metrics table
    print(metrics_df)

Logistic Regression      0.77       0.78    0.75      0.77     0.85
Random Forest            0.80       0.77    0.83      0.79     0.87
XG Boost                 0.80       0.77    0.84      0.79     0.87
ANN                      0.77       0.76    0.79      0.77     0.85

AUC - ROC Plot is a great way to determine the best model. It is the area under the curve for each model. The random classifier is 0.5 (Worst performing).

  • Best Performer : Ensembe Models (Random Forest and XGBoost) achieved the highest AUC-ROC of 0.87 with best balance of precision and Recall.
  • Logistic Regression was efficient. But, it lags both recall - precision and overall ability to capture non-linear relationship
  • ANN : Due to not enough data and despite being theoretical powerful, It does not outperform Ensemble model (Random Forest and XGBoost) and incur high computation

The above results were obtained using the standard threshold of 0.5. Overall, the Random Forest and XGBoost models performed well. However, it would be worthwhile to investigate their performance at different thresholds, such as 0.4 and 0.6. Since the dataset is imbalanced and our primary goal is to capture fraudulent transactions, achieving a high recall is crucial. At the same time, we aim to maintain a reasonable precision, along with high F1 scores and AUC-ROC values.

Result (Thrershold = 0.4)

  • Random Forest is the best performer with highest AUC-ROC (0.88), having high recall (0.9) - Captures 90% of fraud cases, it is critical for imbalance data
  • Trade-off : Decline in precision (0.73) compared to (0.77) in case of threshold = 0.5
  • XGBoost also performed decent similar to random forest
  • Logistic Regressiona and ANN lags in performance compared to Random Forest and XGBoost
  • Overall, for fraud transaction detection (High recall needed) -> Random Forest at threshold = 0.4 is optimal

Final Model Conclusion¶

  • Random Forest and XGBoost are the best models in terms of both AUC-ROC and balanced F1 score across thresholds.
  • Given transactional dataset is imbalance, with fraudulent transactions representing minority (Positive Class), it is important to choose a model that maximizes recall while maintaining a resonably high precision.
  • There was a significant increase in recall from (0.90 to 0.83) for threshold = 0.4 - Desirable for fraud transcation detection
  • Based on the models performance for different threshold, Random Forest with threshold (0.5) performs adequately. However using a threshold (0.4) significantly improves model's ability to detect fraud transcations with slighly reduction in precision. Therefore, Random Forest at threshold 0.4 is the recommended model for detecting fradulant transcations

def get_feature_names(preprocessor):
    output_features = []
    for name, transformer, cols in preprocessor.transformers_:
        last_step = (
            transformer.steps[-1][1]
            if isinstance(transformer, Pipeline)
            else transformer
        )
        names = getattr(last_step, "get_feature_names_out", lambda x: x)(cols)
        output_features.extend(names)
    return output_features


process = preprocessor.fit_transform(X, y)
feature_names = get_feature_names(preprocessor)

        updated_feature_names.append(name)

Conclusion¶

The transactional dataset was provided with fields like Mercant information, transaction details, time , customerid , acoount, etc. The objective was to perform analysis and build a predictive model to determinne wheather a transaction is fradulant

  • Basic Data analysis : Initial Exploration (number of fields, rows) along with basic statistics summaries to understand data
  • Transaction Amount analysis: Histogram and box plot of transaction amount for insight on transcations information
  • Duplicate transcations : Multi Swipe and Reverse transcation were identified
  • Data preprocessing : handling null values, encoding categorical features and Imbalance in data set (Random Downsampling of majority class)
  • Model Training and Evaluation: Multiple ML models like (Logistic Regression, Rnadom Forest, XGBoost and ANN) with threshold 0.4,0.5 and 0.5 respectively was trained and their performance were evaluated

Overall, the Random Forest (threshlod = 0.4) with high recall and resonably high previous is the best choice in detecting in Fradulent transactions. The model has AUC-ROC (0.88) , Recall (0.90) , Precison (0.73) and F1 (0.81) Feature Importance: Customer ID, Merchant Name and Transaction Amount are the most critical feature for identifying fradulant transcation
